name: Fondren Southwest Northbrook Patio Homes, Section 2 P.O.A.
instructions:
When the original declarations were created and recorded in 1977, included was a provision for an HOA to assess, with the agreement of 75% of the homeowners.  Had that occurred, the association would have continued for a period of 30 years, and would have by restriction automatically continued the provision for increments of 10 years.   That appears to have never happened.  At some point, homeowners, including the seller in this transaction, appear to have attempted to request a voluntary fee from the current listing of homeowners through the then named Bellbrook Civic Assn.  It is not clear for what use the monies were intended. That option too has appeared to have not taken off and is currently not active.

The opinion of this tax service is that the association is not active and there is no indication that the association will ever be active.  There are no known amenities that would require an assessment to offset any costs.

name: Intown on Center Street
instructions:
The association does NOT officially bill annual assessments.  However, they DO share the cost of the common expenses which include (1) Landscape bill @ $39.78 per month per unit and (2) electricity for the main entrance gate which is $2.50 per month but is billed in arrears twice yearly totaling $15.00 per six months.

Both bills are paid by Mr. Avila personally, so each owner remits their checks payable to Antonio Avila.

For this closing, proposed for Friday, 8-30-13, collect September landscape @ $39.48 from the new owner payable to Antonio Avila.  As for the electricity, the next billing for approximately $15.00 per owner will be December 2013 for July, 2013 through December 2013.  You may credit the buyer for the sellers portion through the closing date.  The buyer will receive a bill late 2013 for that service and should remitted payable to Antonio Avila. 

IMPORTANT NOTE BELOW FROM THE OWNERS REPRESENTATIVE TO SHARE WITH THE BUYERS IF THE SELLER HAS NOT ALREADY DONE SO:
 
"One other requirement that is worth mentioning now is that there is a parking spot inside the gate that belongs to my (Mr. Avila) property per the property survey.  All the neighbors know this but has caused some confusion in the past and with some recent tenants that have joined the property.  In order to avoid any confusion in the future, I think it is important to mention this to the buyer from the beginning.  Michael can probably clarify this as well."

name: Schuller Street Place
collector: c/o Josephine Li-Avina (term expires upon sale)
contact: Dec. 2014:  Josephine Li - relinquishes after sale to Oladinni
instructions:
As of December 19, 2014, below is the synopsis of the rather unofficial HOA from the seller and current HOA administrator, Josephine Li:

"There is no official HOA. I owned and managed all of the shared expenses between the 3 town homes in the community. The other units would give me an amount which I would deduct from every time there is an expense. We are going to settle with those units on their balances when we sell the house. Then, the 3 of the owners, including the buyers, can decide which one is going to manage the shared expenses.

Here are some notes on how our community manages the expenses. 

1) Gate Electricity Bill - is a little under $10 per month divided by three.  It is currently in my name with Reliant but can be transferred to anyone.

2) Lawn - The current provider charges $27 per visit and comes every two weeks but the community can change the provider if they deem necessary. We have bit greater share of the lawn costs than the other two as we own a bit more of the lawn. Approximately 40/30/30% split.

3) Any other discrete expenses are discussed among the community and costs are shared.  Examples of previous shared costs include painting the gate less than two years ago, driveway lights, weed killer liquid and gate motor re-key."
amenities: No transfer fee.  See particulars above.

name: Parker Court HOA
instructions:
NOTE: PLEASE NOTIFY THE PROPOSED BUYER OF THE FOLLOWING WORKING SCENARIO AT THE COMPLEX OF 6 HOMEOWNERS:
Per a recent seller as of Dec. 11, 2014, "We have no formal HOA within our townhouse complex and no formal procedures for handling common tasks or formal expectations of any homeowner, other that each homeowner will take care of their residence.  Common area concerns are handled informally, through discussions with the other homeowners.  We have shared costs to date on lawn maintenance (or traded the responsibility), driveway maintenance (to date just keeping it clearn), etc.   Years (sic) ago, the common owners agreed to share the cost of planting trees around the complex.  There is no appointed coordinator; residents raise issues and take responsibility for them as they see fit.  It has been a quite workable arrangement in the near six years that I have lived here."
amenities: No transfer fee or deposit is required by the HOA.

name: 1811-1815, 1901 Potomac HOA
instructions:
BELOW IS A STATEMENT FROM THE HOA ADMININSTRATOR: 
I have filled out the information below to the best of my ability.  Also to help the buyers, I have attached a spreadsheet that went to each of the homeowners in our little hood to show the expenses and their allocation.  For example you will see that the lawn fee is for the 6 homes that make up 1811 an 1815 Potomac, whereas the electricity and the phones for the gates are shared by 9 homes -- 1811, 1815 and 1901.   We then have a one time expenses it is allocated based on which homes benefit from the expense -- i.e. gate repair, etc..  A homeowner typically picks up the expense and then we reconcile and adjust when we sent out the next year assessment. 

I hope this helps.  If you have any questions, please do not hesitate to call or if the buyers have any questions I will do my best to answer.  We all work together in our little gated neighborhood to keep costs low but ensure that the value of our homes remains high.

Alex Calicchia
832.651.3895 (mobile)

name: Park at Tangle Lane Association
instructions: NOTE: This association is a GATED Community and requires both a telephone line and electricity and trash collection.   Each homeowner maintains their own property and landscaping but common areas are paid by the common owners in bulk at the time of service.  The current coordinator of expenses is Steve Cagle, a homeowner in the 6 unit complex.  Mr. Cagle pays ALL the bills for both the phone and the electricity for the full year as it is billed at approximately $80.00 per month per homeowner for the common use as noted above.  At the end of the calendar year, Mr. Cagle bills each of the homeowners in arrears for the $80.00+- per month and each of the homeowners write Mr. Cagle a check for those expenses. NO FEES ARE PAYABLE TO "PARK AT TANGLE LANE!" No transfer fee or refinance is levied by this association.
amenities: Upon sale of a property in this small complex, Mr. Cagle will bill the seller of the address being sold at the rate of $80.00 +- per month THROUGH the move out.  The new owner will then be billed at the end of the current year for the balance of the year's expenses for that address.
